He ranks it after the Parzst'ensis 7773 and the Wiedobonensis (V,)‚ and describes all three as ‘of very recent date and vilely interpolated'—lrbri qurilam recentissimi foedissimaque interpolati (p. 45). I shall be able to show, however, that the Harletbnus takes us back to within a few years of Enoch’s discovery, and that the Parisiensis, which was used by Pithon and included by Michaelis among the MSS. on which he founded his critical edition (1868), was directly copied from it at a date considerably later. The Porrsiensis need not be referred to again in any discussion of the text of the Drologue. It has not, and ought never to have been allowed, any independent value whatever.
